Fix #1133: Fix require('winjs') in CommonJS env

This:

  var WinJS = require('winjs');

now works when using WinJS in a CommonJS environment (e.g. browserify).

All of the changes were in requirejs.js which generates the JavaScript at
the head and tail of base.js and ui.js.

To fix this:
  - ui had to declare its dependency on base.js CommonJS-style. ui.js now
    starts with the following code which declares its dependency on base for
    all module styles: AMD, CommonJS, and global/none:

    if (typeof define === 'function' && define.amd) {
      // amd
      define(["./base"], factory);
    } else {
      if (typeof module !== 'undefined') {
        // CommonJS
	factory(require("./base"));
      } else {
        // No module system
	factory(globalObject.WinJS);
      }
    }

  - ui and base had to publish their exports CommonJS-style. ui.js now
    ends with the following code which publishes its exports for all module
    styles: AMD, CommonJS, and global:

    // WinJS always publishes itself to global
    globalObject.WinJS = _WinJS;
    if (typeof module !== 'undefined') {
      // This is a CommonJS context so publish to exports
      module.exports = _WinJS;
    }
    return globalObject.WinJS;
  - js/ui.js is listed as "main" in package.json. Because ui.js depends on
    base.js, this will pull in all of WinJS.

I tested this change with browserify and webpack.

Note that WinJS bundles created with browserify currently lead to an
exception in the browser due to stray BOMs in the file. This is due to
substack/node-browserify#1263. It can be worked around by running
browserify with this flag: --no-detect-globals

Enable WinJS.js output file to work with webpack

The WinJS.js output file didn't work with webpack. The problem was that
our technique for getting ahold of the global object didn't work:

  (function (global) {
    // In here, we wanted global to be the global object.
  })(this);

This techinque failed because webpack executes a module's code within a
function where "this" is not the global object.

We now use this technique:

  var globalObject =
    typeof window !== 'undefined' ? window :
    typeof self !== 'undefined' ? self :
    typeof global !== 'undefined' ? global :
    {};

which gets ahold of the appropriate global object whether its executed on
the browser UI thread, a browser web worker, or node even when used with
webpack.

Fix #637

A second take on a fix for #637. The previous fix broke the scenario where you pass a parented promise to WinJS.UI.Pages.render().

This fix is less intrusive, but requires some work on the part of the developer to handle errors properly. This time the error value of Pages.render() has been modified to be an object that contains a reference to the Page itself. This way you can hook Page.readyComplete yourself and handle the error later:

WinJS.UI.Pages.render(location, element, state)
    .then(function (page) {
        console.log("Pages.render complete");
        return page.readyComplete;
    }, function (errObj) {
        console.log("Pages.render error");
        return errObj.page.readyComplete;
    })
    .then(null, function () {
        console.log("Page error handled");
    });
